artists, and intellectuals. The Fat Studies Reader is a milestone achievement, bringing together fifty-three diverse voices to explore a wide range of topics related to body weight. From the historical construction of fatness to public health policy, from job discrimination to social class disparities, from chick-lit to airline seats, this collection covers it all.Edited by two leaders in the field, The Fat Studies Reader is an invaluable resource that provides a historical overview of fat studies, an in-depth examination of the movement's fundamental concerns, and an up-to-date look at its innovative research.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Jul 2020) 0aObesityxSocial aspects. 0aOverweight persons. 4aEdited. 4aReader. 4aconcerns. 4aexamination. 4afield. 4afundamental. 4ahistorical. 4ain-depth. 4ainnovative. 4ainvaluable. 4aleaders. 4alook. 4amovements. 4aoverview. 4aprovides. 4aresearch. 4aresource. 4astudies. 4athat. 4aup-to-date. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Gender Studies.2bisacsh1 aRothblum, Esther, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aSolovay, Sondra, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aWann, Marilyn08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertNYUP Backlist 2000-2013z978311070644440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780814777435423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780814777435.jpg  a978-3-11-070644-4  NYUP Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK